accessibility.text: 1)	Skill acquisition – skill requirements for the bassist were consistently seen as less rigorous – ‘the easiest instrument to play well’ ‘it’s very easy to start off on, because it has four strings instead of six’.
a.	An assumption that women will be drawn to instrument with lower learning curve due to starting to play later. (median age 19, vs 13 for men in Clawson’s sample).
2)	Demand/value/power – the pool of bass players is fairly small – high-demand, and allows you to play in bands.
a.	Queuing theory emphasises that progress for women requires low prestige and rejection of their jobs by men. ‘The bass has been seen as the resort of failed guitar players’.
b.	The guitar retains prestige. ‘The guitar is the star’.
